  "why": "BET enforces both semantic consistency and naturalness where applicable. For single-model testing (ST) the oracle requires the original ground-truth label, so semantic equivalence is applicable; BET constrains all pixel changes with an L_infty bound (L∞ = 13/255) and implements its mutator so each pixel is always within ±ε of the original value (bytes flip between Eo ± ε rather than accumulating changes). This prevents cumulative distortion across iterations and keeps mutants realistic (pixel-space, integer-valued perturbations). The paper also notes BET adds perturbations directly on integer pixel values (no continuous-to-discrete rounding loss), yielding an Inact-Rate of 0%, which supports that semantic/natural image properties are preserved. These design choices meet the High definition (control perturbation relative to the original seed and ensure naturalness) from the metric.",
  "evidence": "Page 7, Section 3.5 Mutator: \"we limit the perturbations to each byte to two choices {+ε, −ε} ... Given an original input Eo, a current best test case Eb derived from it, and a slice to add perturbations, we examine each byte in the slice and add perturbations accordingly. Assuming the byte being examined is the i-th byte ... if Eb[i] = Eo[i], we randomly add perturbation value of +ε or −ε to this byte. If Eb[i] = Eo[i] − ε, we change this byte to Eo[i] + ε. Otherwise, Eb[i] = Eo[i] + ε must hold and we change this byte to Eo[i] − ε.\"; Page 8, Section 4.1 Experimental Setup (Hyperparameters): \"We use the widely used L∞ metric ... we choose values that make them perform relatively well, i.e., L∞ = 13/255 on all datasets (all compared methods use the same setting).\"; Page 3, Section 2.2 Related Work (ST definition): \"ST only focuses on one target model C to find error-inducing inputs and requires labels for test data. For example... an error-inducing input x_err is found if C(x_err) ≠ l.\"; Page 9, Section 4.3 Results (Inact-Rate): \"The Inact-Rate of BET is 0.0%. The perturbations are directly added on pixel values as integers, BET does not suffer the inactivation issue.\""
